==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mince
<hw>Mince</hw> <pr>(m⟦icr⟧ns)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Minced</conjf> <pr>(m⟦icr⟧nst)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Minging</conjf>
<pr>(m⟦icr⟧n"s⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>minsian</ets> to
grow less, dwindle, fr. <ets>min</ets> small; akin to G.
<ets>minder</ets> less, Goth. <ets>minniza</ets> less, <ets>mins</ets>
less, adv., L. <ets>minor</ets>, adj. (cf. <er>Minor</er>); or more
likely fr. F. <ets>mincer</ets> to mince, prob. from (assumed) LL.
<ets>minutiare</ets>. ⟦root⟧101. See <er>Minish</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To cut into very small pieces; to chop fine; to
hash; <as>as, to <ex>mince</ex> meat</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To suppress or weaken the force of; to extenuate; to
palliate; to tell by degrees, instead of directly and frankly; to clip,
as words or expressions; to utter half and keep back half of; <as>as, he
doesn't <ex>mince</ex> words</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I know no ways to <qex>mince</qex> it in love, but directly to say
-- ⟦ldquo⟧I love you.⟦rdquo⟧</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Siren, now <qex>mince</qex> the sin,⟦br⟧
And mollify damnation with a phrase.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If, to <qex>mince</qex> his meaning, I had either omitted some
part of what he said, or taken from the strength of his expression, I
certainly had wronged him.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To affect; to make a parade of.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mince</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mince
<hw>Mince</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To walk with short
steps; to walk in a prim, affected manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The daughters of Zion are haughty, and walk with stretched forth
necks and wanton eyes, . . . <qex>mincing</qex> as they go.</q>
<rj><qau>Is. iii. 16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I 'll . . . turn two <qex>mincing</qex> steps⟦br⟧
Into a manly stride.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To act or talk with affected nicety; to affect
delicacy in manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mince</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mince
<hw>Mince</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A short, precise step; an affected
manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mince-meat</ent>⟦br⟧
